T1  - Being Emotional During Decision Making—Good or Bad? an Empirical Investigation
AU  - Seo, Myeong-Gu
AU  - Barrett, Lisa Feldman
Y1  - 2007/08/01
PY  - 2007
DA  - 2007/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amj.2007.26279217
DO  - 10.5465/amj.2007.26279217
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 923
EP  - 940
VL  - 50
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This paper examines the link between affective experience and decision-making performance. In a stock investment simulation, 101 stock investors rated their feelings on an Internet Web site while making investment decisions each day for 20 consecutive business days. Contrary to the popular belief that feelings are generally bad for decision making, we found that individuals who experienced more intense feelings achieved higher decision-making performance. Moreover, individuals who were better able to identify and distinguish among their current feelings achieved higher decision-making performance via their enhanced ability to control the possible biases induced by those feelings.
AB  - This paper examines the link between affective experience and decision-making performance. In a stock investment simulation, 101 stock investors rated their feelings on an Internet Web site while making investment decisions each day for 20 consecutive business days. Contrary to the popular belief that feelings are generally bad for decision making, we found that individuals who experienced more intense feelings achieved higher decision-making performance. Moreover, individuals who were better able to identify and distinguish among their current feelings achieved higher decision-making performance via their enhanced ability to control the possible biases induced by those feelings.
